        <description>
          The discovery of Enceladus’ icy jets and their role in creating Saturn’s E-ring is one of the top findings of the Cassini mission to Saturn. Further Cassini mission discoveries revealed strong evidence of a global ocean and the first signs of potential hydrothermal activity beyond Earth - making this tiny Saturnian moon one of the leading locations in the search for possible life beyond Earth. This poster is from a set of new "travel posters" from NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory, Pasadena, California, which envision a day when the creativity of scientists and engineers will allow us to do things we can only dream of now. The posters in the set depict various cosmic destinations including Mars, Jupiter's moon Europa, Saturn's vapor-spewing moon Enceladus, and the dwarf planet Ceres. You can take a virtual trip to 14 alien worlds, and maybe even plaster your living room with planetary art, via the new, futuristic space tourism posters. The posters are the brainchild of The Studio at JPL, a design and strategy team that works with JPL scientists and engineers to visualize and depict complex science and technology topics. Their work is used in designing space missions and in sharing the work of NASA/JPL with the public. The Archive copy is a high resolution TIFF image that can be downloaded from the digital library and printed 20 x 30 inches in high-resolution.
        </description>

        <description>
          Like Luke Skywalker’s planet “Tatooine” in Star Wars, Kepler-16b orbits a pair of stars. Depicted here as a terrestrial planet, Kepler-16b might also be a gas giant like Saturn. Prospects for life on this unusual world aren’t good, as it has a temperature similar to that of dry ice. But the discovery indicates that the movie’s iconic double-sunset is anything but science fiction. This poster is from a set of new "travel posters" from NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory, Pasadena, California, which envision a day when the creativity of scientists and engineers will allow us to do things we can only dream of now. The posters in the set depict various cosmic destinations including Mars, Jupiter's moon Europa, Saturn's vapor-spewing moon Enceladus, and the dwarf planet Ceres. You can take a virtual trip to 14 alien worlds, and maybe even plaster your living room with planetary art, via the new, futuristic space tourism posters. The posters are the brainchild of The Studio at JPL, a design and strategy team that works with JPL scientists and engineers to visualize and depict complex science and technology topics. Their work is used in designing space missions and in sharing the work of NASA/JPL with the public. The Archive copy is a high resolution TIFF image that can be downloaded from the digital library and printed 20 x 30 inches in high-resolution.
        </description>

description: Cristiani Hugenii Zulichemii, Const. f. Systema Saturnium.
Schematic of Saturn's rings.

In 1656, Christiaan Huygens came very close to solving a mystery about Saturns rings. Because of the way that Saturn rotates on its axis, the rings do not always appear as a complete circle. Since the rings do not always appear as a complete circle, people wondered, Are there really rings around Saturn? This image is Christiaan Huygens depiction of the changing appearance of Saturn and its rings. Using a state of the art telescope from that era, Huygens declared that Saturn had a solid ring that was extremely flat and disconnected from the surface of the planet. He was nearly correct! Today, we know that Saturn has multiple rings made of mostly ice. Saturn's ring system extends far beyond the planet and is so wide that 22 planet Earths could fit across them. Yet, in its thinnest places, the rings are only as tall as a three-story building. Saturn is so far away that it would take six years to get there by space travel; but despite how far away it is from us here on Earth, we can still see parts of its rings from our own planet.

description: The beauty of the heavens : a pictorial display of the astronomical phenomena of the universe : one hundred and four coloured scenes, illustrating a familiar lecture on astronomy
The Planetary System

If we had to guess, wed say youre reading this from somewhere on planet Earth. The ancient Greeks used the word planet, which means wanderer, to describe the huge objects they saw in the sky because they appear to move while the stars in the background appear to stand still. While now we know that everything is moving, including the stars, the name planet stuck with us. According to how scientists define the term, there are eight planets in oursolar system, meaning, objects that orbitthe Sun. The sun uses gravity to keep the planets spinning in orbit, and it also provides heat and light to each of them. The four inner planets are Mercury, Venus, Earth, and Mars. Composed of mostly rock and metal and with solid surfaces, these are given the term terrestiral or Earth-like. The four outer planets are Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus, and Neptune. They are all much larger than the inner planets; Jupiter is larger than the seven other planets combined! In addition to their size, they also differ from the inner planets in that they have no solid surfaces; they are made of liquid and gases, and they each have a ring system and several moons. Not such a small world, after all.

description: Research in Progress

On black ground, a male figure viewed from the mid-torso, rendered in white hatching lines; his head shown in profile at left and right to suggest movement, his left arm rendered in four positions with curving lines to indicate motion. Surrounding the left eye of the frontal face, a square shows a small section of the man's face in full color. Behind the figure, horizontal yellow, red, and blue lines recede to the horizon. Dotted white lines emerge from the man's eyes, the ones at center pointing up towards an array of colorful graphics. At top, printed white text: UNDERSTANDING TAXES '79; below, a curving group of images including the American flag; a portrait of Abraham Lincoln; the planet Saturn; a portrait of Franklin Delano Roosevelt; a hand holding a Social Security card; a silver dollar coin, a purple hot-air balloon with the yellow label "W-2"; the central oval medallion of a one-dollar bill, the number"1" inside; a purple rose; a hand holding a card printed with "APRIL 15" in black block letters; a white line drawing similar to a plug or nuclear radiation symbol, and a white dove carrying a sheet with "1040-A" printed in orange in its beak. Below these icons, a curving row of purple question marks. Centered below, the earth printed in turquoise. Composition contained within white framing line.

At top, printed white text: UNDERSTANDING TAXES '79; below, a curving group of images including the American flag; a portrait of Abraham Lincoln; the planet Saturn; a portrait of Franklin Delano Roosevelt; a hand holding a Social Security card; a silver dollar coin, a purple hot-air balloon with the yellow label "W-2"; the central oval medallion of a one-dollar bill, the number"1" inside; a purple rose; a hand holding a card printed with "APRIL 15" in black block letters; a white line drawing similar to a plug or nuclear radiation symbol, and a white dove carrying a sheet with "1040-A" printed in orange in its beak. Below these icons, a curving row of purple question marks. Centered below, the earth printed in turquoise. Composition contained within white framing line.
